Hypothesis Testing with R ¶

T-test for population means ¶

Statistical Inference ¶

  • Statistical inference is the process of drawing conclusions about a population on the basis of measurements or observations made on a sample.

  • The conclusion of a statistical inference is a statistical proposition().

  • Some common forms of statistical proposition:

    • point estimate(), a particular value that best approximates some parameter of interest;
    • interval estimate(), a confidence interval;
    • rejection of a hypothesis()

Point Estimate ¶

Common ways to find the point estimate:

  • Moment estiamtor: The method of moments was introduced by K. Pearson and P. Chebyshev in 1887, and it is one of the oldest methods of estimation. This method is based on law of large numbers, which uses all the known facts about a population and apply those facts to a sample of the population by deriving equations that relate the population moments to the unknown parameters. We can then solve with the sample mean of the population moments. However, due to the simplicity, this method is not always accurate and can be biased easily. Let $(X_1, X_2,X_n)$ be a random sample from a population having p.d.f. (or p.m.f) $f(x,), = (_1, _2, , _k)$. The objective is to estimate the parameters $_1, _2, ..., _k$. Further, let the first k population moments about zero exist as explicit function of , i.e. $_r = _r(_1, _2,, _k)$, r = 1, 2, , k. In the method of moments, we equate k sample moments with the corresponding population moments. Generally, the first k moments are taken because the errors due to sampling increase with the order of the moment. Thus, we get k equations $_r(_1, _2,, _k) = m_r$, r = 1, 2, , k. Solving these equations we get the method of moment estimators (or estimates) as$ m_r = {X_i^r\over n}$. See also generalized method of moments.
  • MLE:The method of maximum likelihood, due to R.A. Fisher, is the most important general method of estimation. This estimator method attempts to acquire unknown parameters that maximize the likelihood function. It uses a known model (ex. the normal distribution) and uses the values of parameters in the model that maximize a likelihood function to find the most suitable match for the data. Let $X = (X_1, X_2, ... ,X_n)$ denote a random sample with joint p.d.f or p.m.f. $f(x, )$ ($$ may be a vector). The function $f(x, )$, considered as a function of $$, is called the likelihood function. In this case, it is denoted by L(). The principle of maximum likelihood consists of choosing an estimate within the admissible range of , that maximizes the likelihood. This estimator is called the maximum likelihood estimate (MLE) of . In order to obtain the MLE of , we use the equation ${{\rm d logL}()\over{\rm d}_i}=0, i = 1, 2, , k. $If is a vector, then partial derivatives are considered to get the likelihood equations.

Interval Estimate ¶

Write a function to calculate the confidence interval:

In [1]:
# import the data set
library(tidyr)
library(palmerpenguins)
penguins <- drop_na(penguins)
x <- penguins$body_mass_g
xbar <- mean(x)
s <- sd(x)
n <- length(x)
alpha <- 0.05
t.quantile <- qt(alpha/2, df = n - 1, lower = FALSE)
ci.lower <- xbar - t.quantile * s / sqrt(n)
ci.upper <- xbar + t.quantile * s / sqrt(n)
c(ci.lower, ci.upper)
  1. 4120.25613262312
  2. 4293.857981491

Hypothesis testing ¶

Remarks:

  • There are two kinds of alternative hypothesis, two-sides and one-sides. The main difference is the p-value.
  • For the one-side case, we don't need to calculate the absolute probability. For example, if we want to test whether < 0 or not, the alternative hypothesis becomes $$H_1: \mu < \mu_0. $$ As a result, we only reject $H_0$ if your observation of $T$ is too small. The p-value becomes $$p-value=P(T<t)=P(T<-2.106)=0.018.$$

Write a function to calculate the p-value:

In [2]:
# import the data set
library(palmerpenguins)
penguins <- drop_na(penguins)
x.bar <- 4207.057
mu0 <- 4300
s <- 805.216
n <- 333
t <- (x.bar-mu0)/(s/n^0.5)
t
2*pt(- abs(t),df=n-1)
-2.10632997054272
0.0359259032427813

Rejection rejion:

The steps 5 and 6 can be replaced by the rejection region method.

  • Given a significance level $$ and based on the distribution of the test statistic, we can calculate the threshold of the t-value.
  • For example, for the two-tailed hypothesis, we should reject the null hypothesis if the t-value is too small or too large. Given that $ = 0.05$,$$P(|T|>t_{\alpha /2,n-1})=\alpha,$$where $t_{\alpha /2,n-1}$ is the $\alpha/2$ upper-quantile of the $t_{n-1}$ distribution, which can be calculated by
In [3]:
qt(0.05/2,df=n-1,lower=FALSE)
1.96713505671906
  • Note that our observation is -2.106, which falls into the rejection region, and then we reject the null hypothesis at the significance level 0.05.

Nonparametric tests with R ¶

Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test ¶

  • The Wilcoxon signed-rank test was proposed in Wilcoxon (1945).
  • It can be used in both one- and two-sample case.

One sample case ¶

  • Let $ Y_1, , Y_n$ be i.i.d. random variables with the common absolutely continuous distribution $F$.
  • $F$ distribution is symmetric.
  • $$: median of $F$.
  • Suppose that we want to test $$H_0:\mu = 0,~~{\rm v.s.}~~H_1:\mu \neq 0.$$

Rank of data

  • The data can be ordered from smallest to largest.
  • For example, if we observed $$x_1=3,~x_2=5,~x_3=9,~x_4=10,~x_5=4$$
  • Then the ordered data is $$x_{(1)}=x_1=3,~x_{(2)}=x_5=4,~x_{(3)}=x_2=5,~x_{(4)}=x_3=9,~x_{(5)}=x_4=10$$
  • We have $$r_1=1,~r_2=3,~r_3=4,~r_4=5,~r_5=2.$$
In [14]:
x <- c(3,5,9,10,4)
rank(x)
  1. 1
  2. 3
  3. 4
  4. 5
  5. 2

Wilcoxons statistic

  • Let $R_1,...,R_n$ be the rank of $$|Y_1 \mu_0|, , |Y_n \mu_0|.$$
  • Define $$\Psi_i=\left\{ \begin{aligned} 0~~~~ & {\rm if}~ Y_i-\mu_0<0, \\ 1~~~~ & {\rm if}~ Y_i-\mu_0 \geq 0. \\ \end{aligned} \right. $$
  • The Wilcoxon's signed rank statistic is defined by$$W = \sum_{i=1}^n R_i\Psi_i.$$
In [15]:
y <- c(3,5,9,10,4)
mu0 <- 5
(y.cen.abs <- abs(y-mu0))
(r <- rank(y.cen.abs))
(psi <- (y > mu0))
(w <- sum(r*psi))

A large sample Wilcoxon signed rank test

Theorem:

When $H_0: \mu=\mu_0$ is true, we have $$E(W)=\frac {n(n+1)}{4},~~~ Var(W)=\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{24}.$$ Also, for $n\geq12,$ the distribution of $$Z=\frac{W-\frac{n(n+1)}{4}}{\sqrt \frac {n(n+1)(n+2)}{24}}\to N(0,1)$$

Theorem:

Let $w$ be the signed rank statistic based on $n$ independent observations, each drawn from a continuous and symmetric pdf, where $n 12$. Let $$Z=\frac{W-\frac{n(n+1)}{4}}{\sqrt \frac {n(n+1)(n+2)}{24}}.$$

  • To test $H_0 : = _0$ and $H_1 : > _0$ at the $$ level of significance, we reject $H_0$ if $z > z_$.
  • To test $H_0 : = _0$ and $H_1 : < _0$ at the $$ level of significance, we reject $H_0$ if $z < z_$.
  • To test $H_0 : = _0$ and $H_1 : \neq _0$ at the $$ level of significance, we reject $H_0$ if $z < z_$ or $z > z_\alpha$.
  • The $p$-value can be calculated.

hist(y)

We want to test $$H_0 : = 28~~~ {\rm v.s.}~~~H_1 : > 28. $$

Testing Paired data ¶

  • A Wilcoxon signed rank test can also be used on paired data to test $H_0:\mu_D=0,$ where $\mu_D=\mu_X-\mu_Y.$
  • Suppose we have a random sample of size $n$, $(x_i,y_i)$, $1 i n$, and let $$d_i=x_i-y_i.$$
  • Let $r_i$ be the rank of $|d_i|$ in the set $$|d_1|,...,|d_n|.$$
  • Define $$\phi_i=I(x_i>y_i).$$
  • Let $$w=\sum_{i=1}^n r_i\phi_i.$$

Example

Hamilton depression scale factor measurements in 9 patients with mixed anxiety and depression, taken at the first (x) and second (y) visit after initiation of a therapy (administration of a tranquilizer).

We want to test $$H_0 : \mu_X = \mu_Y ~~{\rm v.s.}~~ H_1 : \mu_X > \mu_Y .$$

In [25]:
x <- c(1.83, 0.50, 1.62, 2.48, 1.68, 1.88, 1.55, 3.06, 1.30)
y <- c(0.878, 0.647, 0.598, 2.05, 1.06, 1.29, 1.06, 3.14, 1.29)
wilcox.test(x,y,paired=TRUE, alternative = "greater")

	Wilcoxon signed rank exact test

data:  x and y
V = 40, p-value = 0.01953
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is greater than 0

Testing two independent random samples ¶

  • Let $X_1,...,X_n$ and $Y_1,...,Y_m$ be two independent random samples of sizes $n$ and $m$ from $f_X$ and $f_Y$, respectively.
  • For $1 i n + m$, let $R_i$ be the rank of the ith observation in the combined sample, and let $$\Psi_i=\left\{ \begin{aligned} 1~~~~ & {\rm if}~ {\rm the}~i~{\rm~th~observation~came~from~} f_X, \\ 0~~~~ & {\rm if}~ {\rm the}~i~{\rm~th~observation~came~from~} f_Y. \\ \end{aligned} \right.$$
  • Define $$W=\sum_{i=1}^{n+m}R_i\Psi_i.$$

Example

Permeability constants of the human chorioamnion (a placental membrane) at term ($x$) and between 12 to 26 weeks gestational age ($y$). The alternative of interest is greater permeability of the human chorioamnion for the term pregnancy.

In [27]:
x <- c(0.80, 0.83, 1.89, 1.04, 1.45, 1.38, 1.91, 1.64, 0.73, 1.46)
y <- c(1.15, 0.88, 0.90, 0.74, 1.21)
wilcox.test(x, y, alternative = "greater",exact = FALSE, correct = FALSE)

	Wilcoxon rank sum test

W = 35, p-value = 0.1103

Monte Carlo Methods for hypothesis tests ¶

Type-I error and Type-II error ¶

Suppose that we wish to test a hypothesis for $$: $$H_0:\theta \in \Theta_0~~~{\rm v.s.}~~~H_1:\theta \in \Theta_1,$$ where $\Theta_0$ and $\Theta_1$ partition the parameter space $\Theta$.

  • Type-I error and Type-II error
  • Type-I error is that we reject $H_{0}$ given that $H_0$ is true.
  • Type-II error is that we fail to reject $H_0$ given that $H_0$ is not true.
  • Power of a test is that we reject $H_0$ given that $H_0$ is not true.
  • In the one-sample t-test, we assume that $X_1,...,X_n \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)$;
  • Consider $$H_0:\mu = \mu_0~~~{\rm v.s.}~~~H_1:\mu > \mu_0,$$
  • The rejection region is: $$\bar{x}\geq \mu_0 + t_{\alpha,n-1}\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}.$$
  • Then what is the type-I error?
  • Type-I error equals to $\alpha$!

Central limit theorem If we don't know the distribution of $\{X_i\}_{i=1}^n$, then how do we construct the confidence interval?

  • By the central limit theorem, we know that $$\frac{\bar{X}-\mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\implies N(0,1)$$
  • By the law of large numbers $$s^2=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}{n}(X_i-\bar{X})^2\stackrel{P}{\longrightarrow}\sigma^2.$$
  • Therefore, $$\frac{\bar{X}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}=\frac{\bar{X}-\mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\times \frac{\sigma}{s}\implies N(0,1).$$
  • Moreover, as $n\to \infty$, $$t_{\alpha,n-1}\to z_{\alpha},$$
  • Hence, $$P(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}\geq t_{\alpha,n-1})\to P(N(0,1)\geq z_{\alpha})=\alpha$$
  • $n$ttP
  • $n$:$$P(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}\geq t_{\alpha,n-1})$$ Monte Carlo method:
In [2]:
n <- 20
alpha <- 0.05
mu0 <- 1
M <- 10000
t_value <- numeric(M)
set.seed(308)
for (j in 1:M){
x <- runif(n, mu0 - 1, mu0 + 1) #x
t_value[j] <- (mean(x) - mu0)/(sd(x) / sqrt(n)) #  t 
}
is.reject <- (t_value > qt(alpha, df = n - 1, lower = FALSE))
mean(is.reject)
0.0518
In [3]:
n <- 20
alpha <- 0.05
mu0 <- 1
M <- 10000
p_value <- numeric(M)
set.seed(308)
for (j in 1:M){
x <- runif(n, mu0 - 1, mu0 + 1)
p_value[j] <- wilcox.test(x, mu = 1, alternative = "greater")$p.value   # Wilcoxon 
}
is.reject <- (p_value < alpha)
mean(is.reject)
0.0498
